    <fr:title text="Projective modules are direct summands of free modules › "><fr:link href="hmlg-002I.xml" title="Projective modules are direct summands of free modules" addr="hmlg-002I" type="local">Projective modules are direct summands of free modules</fr:link> › </fr:title>
    <fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon>
  </fr:frontmatter>
  <fr:mainmatter>
  <fr:p>A free module evidently projective. If <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is a direct summand of a projective module <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex>, then we can extend any map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  B]]></fr:tex> to <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex> by zero. Then the projectivity of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[Q]]></fr:tex> implies that of <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>

  <fr:p>On the other hand, suppose <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is projective, then we have an epimorphism <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[R^{\oplus  |P|} \twoheadrightarrow  P]]></fr:tex>. The identity map <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P \to  P]]></fr:tex> lifts against this epimorphism to a splitting of it, hence <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[P]]></fr:tex> is its direct summand.</fr:p>
</fr:mainmatter>
